A curse of self-sabotage that many of you insist on casting upon yourselves is, “I know that already.” It’s a recitation that blocks out knowledge and stifles growth. Here’s the thing: 

While you may be aware of a technique or a concept’s existence, this doesn’t mean that you’re utilizing it PROPERLY or that you have used it REPEATEDLY enough to reap the benefits in terms of strength, stamina, and muscle memory. I beg of you, stop sabotaging yourself 🙏🏽😩. Learn to be with the discomfort of not immediately excelling at a particular skill—it’s ok. Feel frustrated, embarrassed, defeated, or even bored—FEEL IT!!!! Have a moment. And then resume the work 😌💁🏾‍♂️. Running to something new, every single time you fail to receive immediate gratification, will not grow your instrument.  Often with this work, the only way out… is through. 🧘🏾 

#MemoirsOfAVocalCoach #AApproach #BuildYourVoice #HealYourVoice

If power/intensity/volume has been elusive for you, it is very likely because you’ve been working against the very nature of your instrument. Stop trying to “project”, and learn to compress the air within you. I’ll be going into greater detail on this topic on my Patreon 🙂 (link in bio).

This is your diaphragm. 

Housed within your rib cage, 360 degrees, it’s probably much bigger than you’ve been led to believe. Also, please note the fact that it is NOT in your belly. 

ALL breathing is diaphragmatic (yes, even when you’re breathing “wrong”), as the diaphragm is our primary muscle of respiration.  There simply is no breathing without it. 

In the @aapproach method, we teach singers how to skillfully 🗣️GET OUT OF THE WAY, and allow the diaphragm to do its job efficiently. The result is a voice that feels and sounds body-connected—stable, grounded, healthy and responsive to your mental commands. #AApproach #BuildYourVoice #HealYourVoice

Stumbling upon pics like this reminds me that I have LIVED. I still remember quitting my job (teaching vocal music at a boarding school) after the release of my first independent album and my first magazine feature (in a German publication that I couldn’t even read 😂). People in my life were so confused. “How are you able to quit? You’re not famous!”. My response: “I’m not famous HERE in the states. But, thankfully, they’re buying my album in Korea, Japan, Germany, The Netherlands, etc.” Thanks to the internet, I was able to support myself as an independent artist and vocal coach. It was wild to see people as far away as Israel and Tokyo performing covers of my song “Say Goodbye”. To be clear, it was still a financial struggle at first, but I had amazingly loyal fans & a growing number of devout private students. After walking away from a major label deal, it felt empowering to see progress on my own terms. #MemoirsOfAVocalCoach #TBT

16 years ago 😳 I walked away from a soul-crushing major label record deal. The A&R told me, “You’ll regret this. You need us! No one knows who you are! You NEED us!”. I realized they were right; no one knew who I was 🤷🏽‍♂️ . I needed to find my own audience.  So when I first began posting on YouTube, my content consisted solely of videos of me singing covers from popular artists. It worked. Hundreds of followers became thousands. Just from singing covers, I became one of the top musician channels on YouTube (they literally used to post your rankings, by category, on your channel page 😄 IYKYK). As a “thank you” to my fans, I shared my secret passion for voice training; I posted a basic vocal warmup video. And it BLEW UP!!! I had worked as a professional vocal coach for major record labels since the age of 19. I LOVED IT, but I never thought the general public would care about vocal technique at all. CLEARLY, I was wrong. MILLIONS of views and 16 years later, here we are. YouTube granted me what I wanted most—autonomy. I was able to release music when I felt like it, without label pressure.  And my niche passion for voice science grew into a successful full-time business 🙌🏽. It’s been a wild ride, and I look forward to all that is still to come. To those of you who’ve been with me since the beginning, and to those who’ve joined us along the way… 🫶🏽 ❤️❤️❤️ #AApproach #Sweet16 #MemoirsOfAVocalCoach

I’ve said this in the past, but I’ll say it again 😌: I remember being so confused as a kid, hearing the discourse about how TV moms like Clair Huxtable were “unrealistic”. I was confused, because that was MY mom: clever and strong, beautiful and charming, and—of course—loving.  For many people, mother-child relationships are very complicated. I get that. Thankfully, that simply hasn’t been the case for me. I’m not bragging; I didn’t earn it. I lucked out. It’s never been complicated for my mom. “I’m introducing you to the best teacher you’ve ever had—you.” I say this to my students every day, because I want to make it clear that you cannot attain vocal mastery by following a strict set of rules. Your vocal instrument is not only unique in comparison to others; it changes DAILY in response to environmental, physical, and mental stressors. So you must learn to tune in, listen to your body, and respond to the cues it is giving you in that moment.  Anything less will lead to frustration: hence the commonly held belief that “the voice” is temperamental. It’s not that the voice is unruly, but rather that we singers tend to be crappy listeners to what our vocal instrument is trying to tell us 😅, choosing instead to focus strictly on the sound. But that’s working backwards. 

Vocal consistency comes when you learn to meet your voice where it’s at in the moment. This means pressing pause on obsessing over whether or not you’re sounding great, taking a few minutes to 🗣️CHECK IN WITH HOW YOUR BODY FEELS. I know this can be a scary concept, as most of us are not taught to listen to—or even trust—the signals from our physiology. As such, most of the techniques in the @aapproach method are designed to awaken and stimulate your reflexive responses. In addition to building strength and flexibility, we’re also developing internal awareness (proprioception) and sensitivity. Learning to distinguish between sensory cues that alert you to potential harm and sensory cues that signal increasing freedom and strength is key. 

I know this can all seem daunting, but it’s ultimately empowering for you as an artist; I promise you can learn to develop an instrument that you can actually TRUST. Need help? Contact us (link in bio) 🙏🏽😌 #AApproach #BuildYourVoice #HealYourVoice

Being able to express yourself freely and clearly is an indicator of health. Your diaphragm works together with your vocal cords to balance airflow with the flow resistance needed to create sound. Then the rest of the body supports this mechanism by handling back pressure and maintaining space for clear resonance.

Underlying all this is the nervous system state, which with acute or chronic stress can make the act of talking, let alone conveying emotion through singing, feel constricted and uncomfortable. 

@ericarceneaux is an amazing example of someone who understands the mechanics at a high level, but knows that the path to sustainable and adaptable vocalization starts with feeling. 

Feeling the state of the throat, the support from the pelvis, the feet on the ground, the closing of the vocal cords, and much more. His programs and patreon are a fantastic resource for connecting the body back with the voice. 

We’ve been inspired by Eric’s work and incorporate vocal awareness into the MovMed system in many ways. This podcast has a ton of value in it. YouTube search “MovMed 25 The Voice” to find it, or see the audio links in our bio.

Thank you @jayleneclarkowens for this powerful piece. 

This topic has been coming up a lot lately in my work with private clients and when I’m interviewed for podcasts & other publications: we have many voices, because society demands that we do. And it makes this demand much louder and more threateningly for some of us than for others. 

I once taught at a school in which I found myself going hoarse at the end of each day. It  took me months to realize that I was instinctively constricting my tone, squeezing my voice higher in an attempt to be less “intimidating” (a critique lobbed at me regularly, when I spoke with my full resonance). The cure was reconnecting my voice to my body and to my truth. Your “true voice” is whatever sound comes out when you allow your voice to be an extension of your true self, without restraint. 

The voice is an extension of your life force energy. The constriction that we hear is a symptom of the constriction within.

I’ll be teaching how to awaken and develop “Passive Support”, one of my favorite elements of vocal technique—a type of training that I rarely speak of outside of my private one-on-one sessions. So I’m really looking forward to sharing this work with you 🙏🏽😊

Vomitare (yes, “to vomit” in Italian) and “Witch’s Voice” are two traditional vocal techniques—called by many names in different cultures—that have withstood the test of time. These are “harsh” sounds that can convey strong/primal emotion. Avoiding these powerfully emotional sounds for the sake of just sounding “pretty” is, in my opinion, a huge mistake 😭. Embrace the ebbs and flows of tension in the voice. It is human. It is soul stirring. It is beautiful 🙏🏽😌 #AApproach #BuildYourVoice #HealYourVoice

Just because air comes through the nose doesn’t mean it’s a high quality breath. Just because it comes through the mouth doesn’t mean it’s a low quality breath.

As laid out in this clip, context matters. Learn to better pull air with the whole body in ways that feel restful AND in ways that get you lots of air quick when you need it. 

In fact building a more complete mouth breath may actually help give you a better nose breath as it helps you sense what less restriction at the airway feels like so you can work to achieve the same ease through the nose.

Lots more great info on breathing during our podcast with @ericarceneaux. “Monkey Bars Ep25 - The Voice with Eric Arceneaux” on YouTube and audio streaming.

Answering some of the questions I get, whenever I mention my Qigong practice:

1️⃣ Qigong is a moving meditation that integrates slow deliberate movements with standing postures and breathing techniques. There are thousands of styles of Qigong. I predominately practice Iron Shirt, Soaring Crane, and Zifagong (though I have studied MANY others). My practice is now somewhat of a gumbo (#NOLAboy 😜) of all that I’ve learned over the years, including complementary methods like Gyrokinesis and Carl Stough’s Breathing Coordination. 

2️⃣ I started practicing at 17 years old, studying under a master who was particularly skilled at harnessing the techniques to improve strength & protection of the voice. Though he was well-rounded in his knowledge, I was OBSESSED with the vocal stuff 😅, foolishly ignoring almost everything else. It wasn’t until I met @trinabordere that I started to really consider the overall full-body health benefits; while she is not a “qigong master” per se, her unique insights and exceptional mastery of the breath-body connection are very much so in alignment with the old-world traditions—triggering innumerable “a-ha moments” over the past 9 years that dramatically deepened my understanding of Qigong principles. 

3️⃣ I began with practice sessions that lasted as briefly as 3mins at a time. I now practice for AT LEAST 40mins per day (often longer). As my practice increased in duration and skill, the health of my body & voice improved to degrees I would never before have believed possible. While I don’t consider myself a “qigong master”, I integrate many traditional practices from around the world into my AApproach Vocal Training Method, including Qigong. Marjorie Montell was said to be a Soprano Assoluta, a rare soprano whose voice was as remarkably agile as it was powerful. She claims to have achieved her incredible vocal skills by learning to focus her attention upon a single point 👌🏽 on her 7th rib 😮. If you’ve ever heard of this obscure legend at all, you’ve likely written off her “magic point” technique as pure quackery—a very justifiable conclusion, to be fair 😅. But you may be surprised to learn that she wasn’t the first or last vocal legend to come to such conclusions about the nature of vocal mastery, and there’s actually quite a bit of science on her side. 

In this class I’ll separate myth from fact; and together we’ll work on tapping into the true power of your diaphragm, utilizing the ✨magical✨ principles of Marjorie Montell.
